04413nam a22006855i 9781501721434DE-B159720220302035458.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220302t20182002nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97815017214347 a10.7591/97815017214342doi  a(DE-B1597)514843  a(OCoLC)1083627991  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 7aSOC0450002bisacsh04a346.7301/32211 aFailer, Judith Lynn, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aWho Qualifies for Rights? :bHomelessness, Mental Illness, and Civil Commitment /cJudith Lynn Failer. 1aIthaca, NY : bCornell University Press, c[2018] 4c©2002  a1 online resource (224 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tIntroduction -- tCHAPTER 1. The Civil Commitment of Joyce Brown -- tCHAPTER 2. The Theory behind Civil Commitment -- tCHAPTER 3. Legal Status and Civil Commitment -- tCHAPTER 4. The History of Commitment Law in the United States -- tCHAPTER 5. The Practice of Civil Commitment -- tCHAPTER 6. To Qualify Rights in Civil Commitment -- tCONCLUSION. Who Qualifies for Rights? -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aWhen does a person become disqualified for some or all of the rights associated with full citizenship? Who does qualify for rights? When mental health workers took Joyce Brown from her "home" on a New York City sidewalk and hospitalized her against her will, she defended herself by asserting her rights: to live where she wanted, to speak to the press to deride the city's policy, and to refuse unwanted psychiatric treatment. In theory, as a United States citizen, Brown possessed rights protecting her from governmental intrusion into her personal life. In practice, those rights were curtailed at the time of her civil commitment.Using the case of Joyce Brown as an example, Judith Lynn Failer explores the theoretical, legal, and practical justifications for limiting the rights of people who are involuntarily hospitalized. By looking at the reasons why law and theory say that some people diagnosed with mental illnesses no longer qualify for the full complement of constitutional rights, the author pieces together basic assumptions about who does, and who should, qualify for rights. Failer's analysis is motivated by her concern that people facing involuntary hospitalization stand to lose the most effective means they have of protecting themselves from abuse—their rights. She concludes that there is insufficient guidance for deciding who qualifies for regular rights and full citizenship. Finally, the author calls for the use of flexible standards to determine who should and who does qualify for rights.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 4aPolitical Science & Political History. 4aPsychology & Psychiatry. 4aPublic Policy. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Poverty & Homelessness.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Backlist 2000-2013z978311053615740uhttps://doi.org/10.7591/978150172143440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781501721434423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781501721434/original  a978-3-11-053615-7  Cornell University Press Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aEBA_STMALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA12STME  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK